   <abstract>This map shows the movements of Union and Confederate troop positions during the Battle of Franklin on November 30, 1864. Union movements are in blue and Confederate movements are in red. Battlefield landmarks and home are indicated including bridges, fords, the toll gate, the saw mill, roads, and railroads. Relief shown by hachures.</abstract>
   <abstract>The Battle of Franklin was one of the worst disasters of the Civil War for the Confederate Army. Confederate Lt. Gen. John Bell Hood's Army of Tennessee conducted numerous frontal assaults against Union forces under Maj. Gen. John M. Schofield and was unable to break through. The Confederates ultimately took Franklin, but at great cost, incurring over six thousand casualties including fourteen generals.</abstract>
